profile1:
The project I worked recently is Shifty planner. It is a shift management and timekeeping system with a focus on the needs of first responders. I developed it using MERN stack. The application allows the first responders to have visibility into their allocated schedule along with options to trade selected dates with their peers. Once a trade is triggered, the app sends email notification to all the peers in the group. The other employees can either `Propose/Reject` the trade. The propose flow allows them to suggest their convenient dates to trade with the original requester. The original requester can then accept the proposal convenient to him from the dates suggested by his/her peers which will then update the calendar for the involved parties.

It's a team project and I worked as a full-stack developer focusing on the Front-end React components including calendar, and trade flows. profile1: This year, I was approached by a front-end developer who needed a stable server and database to power their travel website’s reservation system. Having learned more about the project, I realized I needed to design an infrastructure that could handle hundreds of booking transactions during a soft launch user influx securely and quickly. The challenge was that the soft launch was approaching within two weeks and the budget for server hosting was minimal. By balancing extensive research and practical implementation, I designed a back-end system that routed reservations into a PostgreSQL database, and deployed it on 3 free-tier AWS EC2 instances before the launch date. To mitigate the lack of CPU in the free-tier machines, I included a Nginx load balancer to distribute incoming HTTP requests, achieving 1000 concurrent connections with 10ms of latency. I was elated by this rewarding experience and I took away some life lessons. Going forward, I’d love to work on a team with open communication. It was difficult relying solely on web resources, and I believe I thrive in an environment where I can receive outside feedback, especially from those with greater domain knowledge. I would also celebrate milestones instead of treating it as a large project so that I can properly track my progress. Lastly, I loved the responsibility that comes with developing an entire feature and hope to create and collaborate more in the future.
